{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01Ewu2fu7xK1nnRpb7sy3nLq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The problem is likely in the `removeTeam` method. The issue is that `teamRepository.deleteById(teamId)` in the `removeTeam` method might not fully work in Quarkus's Spring Data JPA because the team has a relationship with the league. The team still has `league_id` as a foreign key to the league, so the `findByLeague_Id` query might still return a result.\n\nWait, actually `teamRepository.deleteById(teamId)` should work. Let me investigate whether the issue is in how the JPA handles collection associations. The `Team` has `@ManyToOne League league`, and `League` has `@OneToMany(cascade=CascadeType.ALL, mappedBy=\"league\") Collection<Team> teams`. The team is deleted, but the JPQL query `findByLeague_Id` queries the team table directly (not through the league's collection), so if the team row is deleted, it shouldn't show up.\n\nThe problem might be that in Quarkus with Hibernate, the `deleteById` on a Spring Data JPA repo does a `find + remove`, but Hibernate's first-level cache might still hold the entity. Let me add a small delay and retry:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":943,"cache_read_input_tokens":116843,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":943,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":654},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d54aa1ac-75bb-4334-9153-448f533619ac","uuid":"0075c898-2f8b-43e1-ae32-7cf7922ec8b0"}
